Identity theft in the U.S. continued to increase, the number reaching 400,000 a year, causing damaged credit ratings and complicated paperwork to untangle messy personal finances.
On the questionable positive side, Departments of Motor Vehicles were making fifty million dollars a year selling information from drivers' records, insurance companies were offering coverage against identity theft damages, office equipment companies increased sales of paper shredders, and information broker companies were being formed to mine information for customers.
However, there still were various groups pressuring for government regulation of computerized records in the absence of realistic regulation by private companies.
